-> [Better Approach] Using Nested Loops and Hash Set - O(n √ó m) Time and O(n) Space
The idea is to find common elements between two arrays without duplicates by:|
‚Äì Using a hash set to track already added elements,
‚Äì Checking each element of a[] against b[], and only adding it to the result if it's present in b[] and not already recorded.

Step By Step Implementation:
a. Initialize an empty hash set for storing result array elements
b. Traverse through a[] and for every element check if it is in b[], then check if it is already in result or not. If in b[] and not in the hash set, then add it to the hash set.
c. Create a result array and copy items of the hash set to the result array and return the result array.

import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.HashMap;
‚Äãclass GfG {
    static ArrayList<Integer> intersect(int[] a, int[] b) {
        ArrayList<Integer> res = new ArrayList<>();
        HashMap<Integer, Integer> seen = new HashMap<>();
‚Äã
        // Traverse through a[] and search every element
        // a[i] in b[]
        for (int i = 0; i < a.length; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < b.length; j++) {
‚Äã
                // If found, check if the element is already 
                // in the result to avoid duplicates
                if (a[i] == b[j] && !seen.containsKey(a[i])) {
                    seen.put(a[i], 1);
                    res.add(a[i]);
                }
            }
        }
‚Äã
        return res;
    }
‚Äã
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] a = {1, 2, 3, 2, 1};
        int[] b = {3, 2, 2, 3, 3, 2};
‚Äã
        ArrayList<Integer> res = intersect(a, b);
‚Äã
        for (int x : res)
            System.out.print(x + " ");
    }
}

